How ? 
Basic scan with Nmap 
nmap 192.168.95.131
This will scan the top 1000 common ports 

#To scan all the ports 
nmap -p- 192.168.95.131
This scan 1-65535 ports

#Aggressive Scan (Real Attacker Behavior) 
Attacker often run 
nmap -sS -sV -0 192.168.95.131 
meaning 
-sS ---Stealth SYN scan 
-sV ---- detect service versions 
-O ----Detect operating system 

#Fast Network Scan 
nmap 192.168.95.0/24
This finds all active machines in the network. 

# How Soc Analyst Detect port scanning 
Soc teams look for 
- one IP connecting to many ports 
-rapid connection attempts 
unusual scanning patterns 
eg: same IP ---- 20+ ports within seconds 

Investigating in Splunk

If network logs exist, analysts search for many connections.

Example search concept:

index=* 
| stats count by src_ip dest_port

Or detecting scanning behavior:

index=* 
| stats dc(dest_port) as ports_scanned by src_ip
| where ports_scanned > 10

Meaning:

one IP scanning many ports
9️⃣ MITRE ATT&CK Mapping

Port scanning corresponds to:

T1046 – Network Service Scanning

SOC teams use this framework to categorize reconnaissance activity.

🔟 SOC Investigation Questions

When analysts see a scan, they ask:

Which IP performed the scan?

Which ports were targeted?

How many ports were scanned?

Was the scan internal or external?

Did the attacker attempt further attacks after scanning?

Typical Attack Chain

Most attacks follow this order:

Reconnaissance
      ↓
Port scanning
      ↓
Brute force / exploitation
      ↓
Privilege escalation
      ↓
Lateral movement

